05685nam a22005895i 9780773589414DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735894147 a10.1515/97807735894142doi  a(DE-B1597)657090  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRA395.C3bH42165 2013eb 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a362.109712231 aFierlbeck, Katherine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHealth Care Federalism in Canada :bCritical Junctures and Critical Perspectives /cWilliam Lahey, Katherine Fierlbeck. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcronyms -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Renewing Federalism, Improving Health Care: Can This Marriage Be Saved? -- tA Multidisciplinary Overview of Health Care Federalism -- tThe Economics of Health Care Federalism: What Do We Know? -- tThe Political Dynamics of Health Care Federalism -- tThe Legal Framework for Intergovernmental Health Care Governance: Making the Most of Limited Options -- tChallenges and Opportunities in Health Care Federalism -- tEconomic Trends and Challenges -- tGovernance Challenges in Implementing Needs-Based Health Human Resources Planning -- tThe Challenges of Measuring the Performance of Health Systems in Canada -- tHealth Care Federalism and the Debate Over Decentralization -- tThe Future of the Provincial Role in Canadian Health Care Federalism -- tThe Future of the Federal Role in Canadian Health Care -- tConclusion: Combining the Knowledge of Federalism Researchers, Health Care Researchers, and Policy Practitioners to Understand and Improve Canadian Health Care Federalism -- tAppendices -- tText of the First Ministers’ Accord on Health Care Renewal, 2003 (First Ministers of Canada 2003) -- tText of the 10-Year Plan to Strengthen Health Care, 2004 (First Ministers of Canada 2004) -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNow that Ottawa has left health care to the provinces, what is the future for Canadian health care in a decentralized federal context? Is the Canada Health Act dead? Health Care Federalism in Canada provides a multi-perspective, interdisciplinary analysis of a critical juncture in Canadian public policy and the contributing factors which have led to this point. Social scientists, legal scholars, health services researchers, and decision-makers examine the shift from a system where Ottawa has played a significant, sometimes controversial role, to one where provinces have more ability to push health care design in new directions. Will this change inspire innovation and collaboration, or inequality and confusion? Providing an up-to-date analysis of health care policy and intergovernmental relations at a crucial time, Health Care Federalism in Canada will be of interest to anyone concerned with the current dynamics and future potential of Canadian health care. Contributors include Greg Marchildon (Canada Research Chair at the Johnson-Shoyama Graduate School of Public Policy in Saskatchewan), Ken Boessenkool (public affairs strategist and former political advisor to Stephen Harper), Adrian Levy (Professor and Head, Department of Community Health and Epidemiology at Dalhousie University), Boris Sobolev (Canada Research Chair at the School of Public and Population Health, University of British Columbia), Gail Tomblin Murphy (Director, WHO Collaborating Centre for Health Workforce Planning and Research), and David Haardt (Department of Economics, Dalhousie University).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, vie